---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import TwoColumnLayout from "../layouts/TwoColumnLayout.astro";
import Ornament from "../components/Ornament.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="Gnomes" description="How autonomous AI agents help maintain this site's content operations.">
  <TwoColumnLayout>
    <article>
      <h1>Gnomes</h1>
      <p class="meta-text">How AI agents help maintain this site</p>
      <p>
        This site uses autonomous AI agent sessions&mdash;called
        <strong>Gnomes</strong>&mdash;to assist with content operations.
        Each Gnome is a Claude-powered session that reads the repository,
        understands its structure, and performs a specific job within
        defined boundaries. This page documents the system as part of the
        site's commitment to <a href="/colophon">transparency about AI
        involvement</a>.
      </p>

      <Ornament glyph="☙" />

      <h2>What Is a Gnome?</h2>
      <p>
        A Gnome is an autonomous AI agent session with two defining
        properties: a <strong>Workplace</strong> and a <strong>Job</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The Workplace is this repository. A reference document called
        <code>GNOMES.md</code> describes the repo's structure, content
        schemas, conventions, and boundaries so that each Gnome can
        orient itself without human hand-holding.
      </p>
      <p>
        The Job is a specific content task assigned by a human. One Gnome
        might annotate posts with pace layer classifications. Another might
        analyze photographs and write alt text. Each Gnome has a handle
        like <code>GNOME_PACER</code> or <code>GNOME_IMGSEE</code> that
        appears in its commit messages and any notes it leaves in the
        codebase.
      </p>
      <p>
        Gnomes are typically Claude Cowork Task sessions&mdash;long-running
        Claude instances that can read files, edit content, and commit
        changes. The specific architecture of a Gnome may vary, but the
        pattern is always the same: read the Workplace, confirm
        understanding, then do the Job.
      </p>

      <Ornament glyph="☙" />

      <h2>Tooling Ecosystem</h2>
      <p>
        Three Claude-powered tools interact with this repository, each
        with a different relationship to the content:
      </p>
      <div class="mermaid-container">
        <pre class="mermaid">
graph TB
    Human["Chris Busse"]

    subgraph tools ["Authoring Tools"]
        Cursor["Cursor IDE"]
        ClaudeCode["Claude Code"]
        Cowork["Claude Cowork Tasks"]
    end

    subgraph repo ["Repository — cb26"]
        GNOMES["GNOMES.md"]
        CLAUDE["CLAUDE.md"]
        Content["src/content/"]
        Scripts["scripts/"]
    end

    subgraph deploy ["Deployment"]
        Astro["Astro Build"]
        CF["Cloudflare Workers"]
        Site["chrisbusse.com"]
    end

    Human --> Cursor
    Human --> ClaudeCode
    Human --> Cowork
    Cowork -->|"reads"| GNOMES
    Cursor -->|"maintains"| GNOMES
    ClaudeCode -->|"maintains"| GNOMES
    Cowork -->|"edits"| Content
    Cursor --> Content
    ClaudeCode --> Content
    repo --> Astro --> CF --> Site
        </pre>
      </div>
      <p>
        <strong>Cursor</strong> and <strong>Claude Code</strong> are
        interactive sessions where a human collaborates with Claude in
        real time. These sessions have full access to the repo and are
        responsible for maintaining structural files like
        <code>GNOMES.md</code> and the content schemas.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Claude Cowork Tasks</strong> are the Gnome sessions.
        They run autonomously, reading <code>GNOMES.md</code> for
        orientation and confining their edits to content files within
        their stated job scope.
      </p>

      <Ornament glyph="☙" />

      <h2>Gnome Lifecycle</h2>
      <p>
        Every Gnome session follows the same sequence:
      </p>
      <div class="mermaid-container">
        <pre class="mermaid">
graph TD
    subgraph setup ["Setup"]
        direction LR
        Define["Human defines Job"] --> Launch["Launch Cowork session"] --> Read["Gnome reads GNOMES.md"]
    end

    subgraph execution ["Execution"]
        direction LR
        Confirm["Confirms understanding"] --> Work["Performs Job"]
    end

    subgraph delivery ["Delivery"]
        direction LR
        Commit["Commits with handle prefix"] --> Report["Summarizes work"]
    end

    Read --> Confirm
    Work --> Commit
        </pre>
      </div>
      <p>
        The human defines the job and launches a Cowork session with a
        standardized prompt that identifies the Gnome by handle. The
        Gnome reads the Workplace reference, confirms its understanding,
        then proceeds to do the work&mdash;committing incrementally with
        messages prefixed by its handle (e.g.,
        <code>GNOME_PACER: add pace layer annotations to 3 posts</code>).
        When finished, it produces a summary of what it accomplished.
      </p>

      <Ornament glyph="☙" />

      <h2>Content Architecture</h2>
      <p>
        The site has three content collections&mdash;posts, photos, and
        talks&mdash;that share a common schema. Gnomes operate on
        specific fields within these collections based on their job:
      </p>
      <div class="mermaid-container">
        <pre class="mermaid">
graph TB
    subgraph schema ["Shared Schema — baseMeta"]
        Title["title, date, description"]
        Meta["tags, draft, category"]
        AI["ai metadata"]
        PL["paceLayers"]
    end

    subgraph collections ["Content Collections"]
        Posts["posts/"]
        Photos["photos/"]
        Talks["talks/"]
    end

    schema --> Posts
    schema --> Photos
    schema --> Talks

    PACER["GNOME_PACER"] -->|"paceLayers"| collections
    IMGSEE["GNOME_IMGSEE"] -->|"alt, description"| Photos
        </pre>
      </div>
      <p>
        The shared schema includes fields for AI metadata&mdash;whether
        AI assisted in creating a piece, which tools were used, and in
        what role. When a Gnome modifies content, this metadata is
        updated to reflect the AI involvement, keeping the provenance
        chain intact.
      </p>

      <Ornament glyph="☙" />

      <h2>Boundaries</h2>
      <p>
        Gnomes operate under a trust-but-verify model with explicit
        boundaries. They may edit content frontmatter, update markdown
        body text, and create new content files following established
        patterns. They may not modify schemas, layouts, components,
        pages, or configuration files. They cannot deploy the site,
        delete files, or install dependencies. Schema changes,
        structural decisions, and deployment remain under human control.
      </p>
      <p>
        When a Gnome encounters ambiguity&mdash;a piece of content where
        the right classification is genuinely unclear, for instance&mdash;it
        leaves a <code>TODO</code> marker with its handle rather than
        guessing. These markers surface during human review and ensure
        that judgment calls stay with a human.
      </p>

      <Ornament glyph="☙" />

      <h2>Transparency</h2>
      <p>
        Every change a Gnome makes is tracked through Git commit history
        with the Gnome's handle in the commit message. Content modified
        by a Gnome carries <code>ai.assisted: true</code> in its
        frontmatter metadata, which is visible in the process colophon
        at the end of each article. The combination of commit
        attribution and content metadata means that Gnome contributions
        are always traceable&mdash;both in the source and on the
        published page.
      </p>
      <p>
        This system is an extension of the editorial principles described
        on the <a href="/colophon">Colophon</a> page: AI tools extend
        reach, but accountability remains with the human.
      </p>
    </article>
  </TwoColumnLayout>
</BaseLayout>

<script is:inline src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/mermaid@11/dist/mermaid.min.js"></script>
<script is:inline>
  mermaid.initialize({
    startOnLoad: true,
    theme: 'neutral',
    themeVariables: {
      fontFamily: '"Roboto Mono", "SFMono-Regular", Menlo, monospace',
      fontSize: '14px',
    },
    flowchart: {
      useMaxWidth: true,
      htmlLabels: true,
      curve: 'basis',
    },
  });
</script>

<style>
  .mermaid-container {
    margin: var(--space-6) 0;
    overflow-x: auto;
  }

  .mermaid-container pre.mermaid {
    border: 1px solid var(--color-rule);
    padding: var(--space-4);
    background: #fafafa;
    overflow-x: auto;
  }
</style>
